A pair fruiting in grass under mature oak in residential landscape. Larger cap: 6.2 cm., aerolate with age. 1-2 pores /mm. Tube length 6-8 mm. Stipe: 7 cm. X 8 mm. at apex, yellow above and below with yellow mycelium at base. Pore surface bruising dark blue-black. Please see Image # 6678 for other bruising. Slight pleasant odor. KOH: bright yellow on cap, orange on flesh and brownish on pore surface. Ammonia: orange on cap, negative on flesh. Olive-brown spore print. This fruiting is a little early for our area, but May temperatures set an all-time record high this year … more like temperatures that we normally see in July.

results.notes:
Field guides typically list it as having no odor, and most people agree. Some people report light, sweet odor. As it turns out, it’s actually the stinkiest mushroom I’ve ever come across, but only SOME people can smell it! It’s so strong I can smell it from several feet away and through a sealed ziplock baggie.
I had a sample and 20 willing, perhaps reluctant, participants all smell the same sample. Of them, only myself and one little boy could smell it. It is a pungent, minty, chemically smell, reminiscent of camphor. (The little boy described it as peppermint.) It’s so strong I can smell it from several feet away and through a sealed ziplock baggie. Since then, I regularly poll people when they find it, and have had several smaller groups of people all sniff the same sample. Only about 1 out of 20 seem to be able to detect the odor.

results.notes:
Found under oak in a spot I go year after year. 100% sure of the ID. The specimens with the redder stipe probably come from a different mycelium than the yellower stipes – they were about 100 feet apart – but the variation is well within observed norms for this species. Note that the bluing is a little slower than normal because the later photos spent a night in my fridge.

And now for the can of worms.

FIRST: I understand that there used to be an accepted North American species that went by the name “Boletus discolor.” It was named after a lookalike European species (common name Scarletina), so we could pretty much assume the name would have had to be changed. (And yes, I know the European species has merged with luridiformis and is in either Neoboletus or Sutorius depending on how that debate works out).

SECOND: I understand that the hemlock-loving subvelutipes is genetically distinct from this oak-loving version, and thus we will need two names.

BUT: I do not have a firm grasp on what used to divide subvelutipes from discolor back in the pre-DNA days. I assume there were reasons for the distinction because the students of mycology were just as smart then as they are today. Only the tools and the knowledge base have changed.

THUS THE QUESTIONS: Is it fair to call the oak-loving version “discolor” for lack of a better name? Should we abandon “discolor” completely as a European name that was misused in N.A.? And what should we call this critter until it has a recognized name? At least one respected expert has suggested “Oak-Loving Subvelutipes” for the nonce, but that is a bit clumsy on the tongue (as if the word subvelutipes on its own wasn’t enough).

Many thanks to all!
